Race for the Crown
Prologue: The Road & The Wolf
Setting: The border between Eastmarch and The Pale.
Time: Mid-day, two days after the events of Kynesgrove.
The Journey
The smell of sulfur and wet marshland fades, replaced by the biting, sterile scent of ice and pine resin. The road climbs steadily upward, the dirt turning to hard-packed permafrost and deep drifts of snow.
Bjorn drives the cart with grim focus. The cart is quiet. The party nurses their woundsΓÇöKyboh cradles his shattered hands, Davinia recovers from the impact. They sit with the judgment of Krusp Fanck hanging over them. Only the creak of wheels and the whistle of the wind fill the silence.
The Ambush
A massive pine trunk crashes down from the ridge. It slams into the road twenty feet ahead of the cart, kicking up a cloud of snow and ice that blocks the path completely.
Bjorn hauls on the reins, bringing the horses to a panicked halt just short of the timber.
A single figure leaps from the ridge above. She lands on the fallen trunk with a ground-shaking thud that cracks the bark. It is a Nord woman, built like the mountains themselves. She wears custom steel plate, hammered and scarred by a hundred battles. Her hair is thick and braided, split perfectly down the middle: one side blood-red, the other spun gold.
She rests a battleaxe the size of a man on her shoulder. She stares at the party with wide, delighted eyes.
"Well now!" she booms, her voice echoing off the canyon walls. "The cart matches the description. The gear matches the rumors. And the smell..."
She sniffs the air deeply.
"Ozone. Old magic. Dragon blood. It is you."
The Encounter: Ylva the Cleaver
She hops down from the log and walks toward the cart with reverence.
"I'm Ylva. They call me the Cleaver. I tracked those Cultists at Kynesgrove for three weeks. I planned to mount their heads on my wall. But when I arrived, the dragon lay dead. The Cultists were ash."
She looks at Kyboh, then at the rest of the party.
"You killed a god. You cleared the board. I have hunted my whole life, but I have never seen a kill like that."
She stops a few feet from the cart and plants her axe in the snow.
"I want in. I want to run with this pack. But I know who you areΓÇöthe Wardens. You take only the strong."
The Challenge: The Audition
Ylva unbuckles her gauntlets and drops them in the snow. She raises her bare fists, bouncing on the balls of her feet.
"I must prove I belong here. I must show you I can hold the line."
She points a finger at Kyboh. She saw the aftermath of his punch; she knows he is the kinetic center of the group.
"You. Whiskers. You hit that dragon super hard. I need to know if I can stand next to you. One round. No weapons. Lets go."
The Mechanic: The Duel
This is a non-lethal skill challenge. Best 2 out of 3 rolls.
Roll 1 (The Clash): Might vs. Might.
Roll 2 (The Dance): Agility vs. Agility.
Roll 3 (The Finisher): Might vs. Agility.
Outcomes:
Kyboh Wins: Ylva picks herself up from the snow, wiping blood from a split lip. She beams. "See? That's what I mean! That power! I can learn so much from you. Please, let me watch your back. I won't let you down."
Ylva Wins: She pins Kyboh or knocks the wind out of him, then immediately offers a hand to pull him up, her face flushed with pride. "I did it! I actually held my own! See? I'm strong enough! I can help you! I promise I'm useful!"

The Journey Continues: Travel Banter
Ylva retrieves her axe and climbs onto the cart. As they travel the final leg to Korvanjund, she settles in, watching the scenery with the relaxed alertness of a apex predator. She answers questions with brutal honesty.
Great question. Ylva is a social creature, an extrovert who just found her new best friends. She would target the person she perceives as the most interesting or relatable.
Given the party makeup:
Kyboh: She just fought him. They have an instant bond.
Davinia: The leader. Ylva respects authority if it's earned.
Saijah: Another hunter? Possible.
Orion/Alfonso: They smell weird (vampire/death). She might be intrigued or wary.
Her Choice: She sits next to Kyboh (the Brawler) or Saijah (the Hunter). She wants to talk shop.
The Icebreaker (Immediately after boarding):
She plops down on a crate, still breathing hard from the fight, radiating heat and energy. She looks at the group, grinning.
"So! The Dragon! Kynesgrove! I saw the corpse on the hill. Who landed the killing blow? Was it the big guy? Or did the little one with the bow get a lucky shot in the eye? Tell me everything. Don't leave out the gory bits."
This opens the floor for the players to brag about their previous exploits, which is exactly what Ylva wants to hear.
GM Reference: Ylva's Responses
If asked about Galmar Stone-Fist:
"He's a bear. Loud, angry, hits hard. I like him. He doesn't waste time with words when a hammer works better. Just don't try to out-talk him. You have to out-shout him, or better yet, out-hit him."
If asked about the War / The Duel:
"I don't get why everyone is so upset. Ulfric challenged Torygg. Torygg accepted. Ulfric won. That makes him High King. That's how it works. Why make it complicated? If the Emperor wanted to keep Skyrim, he should have fought Ulfric himself. The strongest wolf leads the pack. Simple."
If asked about her title ("The Cleaver"):
(She pats her axe affectionately.)
"It's not poetic. I chop things. Wood, ice, trolls, elves. It all cleaves the same if you swing hard enough. It's honest work."
If asked why she is alone:
"Packs are hard to find. Most people... they hesitate. They worry about dying. It ruins the fun. I needed a pack that runs toward the roar. And I found you."
Arrival at the Front
The conversation dies down as the sound of war rises.
Read Aloud:
"The valley narrows. The scent of woodsmoke and old blood replaces the pine. Ahead, the ruins of Korvanjund loom out of the snowstormΓÇöa massive stone temple built into the snowy canyon wall.
The entrance is blocked by war. The banners of the Stormcloaks snap in the wind, and the air rings with the sound of steel and scent of magical ozone.
You have arrived at the Siege Lines."

Section 1: The Siege Lines
Beat 1: The Perimeter (Social Challenge)
The Setting:
The cart rumbles to a halt. The air is thick with the smell of wet wool, blood, and ozone. You are at the edge of the Stormcloak campΓÇöa collection of tents huddled behind a wall of sharpened stakes. The mood is grim. Soldiers are digging graves in the frozen earth.
The Initial Challenge:
A sergeant steps out from behind the barricade. His name is Hroki. He is missing an ear, the wound fresh and cauterized. He signals his archers to draw.
"Halt!" Hroki barks, his voice rough with smoke. "Turn that cart around. This isn't a refugee camp. It's a slaughterhouse. Go back to Kynesgrove before you get added to the pile."
Ylva's Move:
Ylva leaps from the cart, boots crunching in the snow. She walks right up to the spear-point.
"Put it down, Hroki. Unless you want to lose the other ear."
Hroki blinks, lowering the spear a fraction. "Ylva? We thought you died tracking those cultists."
"I found something better," she says, gesturing to the party with a grin. "I found the ones who killed the dragon. I'm bringing you the cavalry."
The Interaction (The Party's Turn):
Hroki looks past Ylva at the party. His eyes linger on Davinia's armor, then on Alfonso's robes. He spits.
"Cavalry? They look like tourists. And that one," he points his spear at Davinia, "is wearing Imperial steel. Why should I let an Imperial walk into my camp while my men are dying?"
The Social Dungeon: Navigating the Perimeter
The party must choose how to respond. This isn't just a single roll; it's a conversation.
Option A: The Soldier's Respect (Davinia)
Dialogue: "Armor doesn't choose sides, Sergeant. Soldiers do. And right now, we're on the side of the living. Do you want help breaking that line, or do you want to keep digging graves?"
Reaction: Hroki glares, then nods slowly. "Fair point. If you can fight, I don't care who forged your breastplate. Just don't stab us in the back."


Option B: The Proof of Power (Kyboh/Orion)
Action: Showing the Dragonbone weapons or loot from Sahloknir.
Reaction: The archers lower their bows, whispering. Hroki's eyes go wide. "Dragonbone... Ylva wasn't lying. Alright. You've earned a pass."


Option C: The Healer's Offer (Danica/Alfonso)
Dialogue: "We have healers. We have potions. We can save the ones you're burying."
Reaction: Hroki's shoulders slump. The aggression drains out of him. "We have three men dying of burns in the medical tent. If you can save them... you're welcome here."


The Result:
Once the party passes the check (roleplay or roll), Hroki steps aside and signals the archers to stand down.
"Open the gate! Let them through!"
He walks up to the cart. "Galmar is at the forward trench. He's been awake for three days. Watch your tone with him; he's in a mood to break heads."
Transition:
The party drives the cart into the camp proper. They pass rows of wounded soldiers who look up with a mix of hope and suspicion. Ahead, the sound of explosions gets louder. The command post awaits.

1. The Ideological Friction (Davinia, Danica, Ylva)
The Scene: The Supply Line
The party navigates the bustling thoroughfare near the mess tents. The smell of boiled leather and thin vegetable stew hangs heavy in the frozen air. A line of soldiers snakes around the supply wagons, waiting for the evening meal distribution. The reality of the siegeΓÇÖs logistics is laid bare.
DaviniaΓÇÖs Observations (The CommanderΓÇÖs Eye)
The Logistics: Davinia notes the markings on the supply crates. They bear the seals of Windhelm and Winterhold, but the wood is old and the crates are light. The supply chain is stretched thin, relying on local contributions rather than a centralized treasury.
The Discipline: She observes the orderliness of the line. Despite the visible hunger, there is no shoving, no hoarding. The discipline holds without officers needing to bark orders.
The Equipment: She sees that weapon maintenance is prioritized over comfort. Whetstones and oil are in abundance, while blankets are threadbare. The army chooses lethality over warmth.
DanicaΓÇÖs Perspective (The HealerΓÇÖs Critique)
Danica moves close to Davinia, her expression tightening as she surveys the condition of the troops. She points out specific details that reveal the human cost of the rebellion.
Signs of Malnutrition: She draws DaviniaΓÇÖs attention to the soldiersΓÇÖ physical stateΓÇöcracked lips, sunken eyes, and the tell-tale lethargy of men preserving calories. She notes that wounds are healing slowly due to lack of protein.
The Moral Failure: She gestures to a young recruit gnawing on a piece of hardtack. She argues that a righteous cause should be able to feed its children. To her, this deprivation is evidence of a leadership that views its people as fuel for a fire, burning them up to prove a political point.
The Contrast: She recalls the well-stocked pantries of the Imperial garrisons they have passed. She posits that stability brings sustenance, while this rebellion brings only hunger and gloryΓÇöand you cannot eat glory.
YlvaΓÇÖs Perspective (The WarriorΓÇÖs Defense)
Ylva walks alongside them, her eyes scanning the same scene but interpreting the data through the lens of the pack. She counters DanicaΓÇÖs observations with her own, highlighting the spirit behind the suffering.
The OfficerΓÇÖs Share: She nudges Davinia to look at the serving table. She points out a captainΓÇöperhaps even GalmarΓÇÖs lieutenantΓÇötaking a bowl of broth that is no fuller than the privateΓÇÖs. She notes that in the Legion, officers dine on wine and roast while the grunts eat slop. Here, the hunger is shared.
Voluntary Sacrifice: She indicates a group of soldiers splitting a single loaf of bread among three, laughing as they do so. She argues that this isn't neglect; it is choice. They are starving themselves to ensure the vanguard has enough supplies for the breach.
The Strength of Will: She remarks that a well-fed dog obeys because it is fed, but a wolf hunts because it is hungry. She claims the Empire buys loyalty with bread, but these men and women pay for their freedom with their own comfort. She respects the price they are willing to pay.
The Synthesis
Davinia is left to stand between them, absorbing the conflicting truths. She sees the validity in DanicaΓÇÖs compassionΓÇöthe suffering is real and terrible. She also sees the validity in YlvaΓÇÖs admirationΓÇöthe resolve is unbreakable. She must walk forward to meet Galmar carrying both the weight of the soldiers' suffering and the respect for their sacrifice.
2. The Faceless Man (Orion & Saijah)
The Scene: The Shadows Behind the Smithy
Orion and Saijah move toward the rear of the camp, ostensibly to check on weapons or find a quiet spot to observe the perimeter. They find themselves in the shadow of a parked supply wagon, away from the direct light of the campfires. The noise of the smiths hammering metal provides a wall of sound that ensures privacy. Leaning against the wagon wheel is a man sharpening a dagger. 
VaronΓÇÖs Appearance (The Uncanny Valley)
To a casual observer, Varon appears to be a standard Breton mercenaryΓÇöround ears, soft features, average build. But to Saijah and Orion, the disguise is imperfect. They notice the unnatural stillness of his posture; he does not shift weight or fidget. Saijah, knowing the sect he comes from, recognizes the faint, white scarring around the ears and jawline where the flesh was surgically reshaped to blend in with Nords and Bretons. He is a living weapon in a skin suit. To Saijah, his posture is unmistakably that of the Root.

The Exchange with Saijah (The Tongue of the Root)
Varon acknowledges Saijah first. He stops sharpening his blade. His expression softens completely, the mask of the mercenary dropping to reveal the genuine warmth of a brother seeing a lost sibling. He does not use the common tongue. Instead, he speaks in Jel.
The Transmission: He reaches out, almost touching her shoulder, then pulls back, respecting her space but conveying the desire for connection.
"Deek-nujei... Oj dimik. Raj-nassa ei. Shunatei u deek. Sithis u uxith-beeko. Ku-vastei... buseek?"
The Translation:
Deek-nujei (Little sister).
Oj dimik (You are vivid/alive).
Raj-nassa ei (The Elders see).
Shunatei (The pain of empathy/Regret) u (is) deek (young/sapling nature).
Sithis (The Void) u (is) uxith-beeko (Nest-friend/Partner/Comfort).
Ku-vastei (The change/catalyst)... buseek? (Why wander?)


The Meaning: "Little sister... you look so alive. The Elders are watching you. This pain you feel from caring so much? It is just growing pains. The Void is a comfort, like a lover. Why do you keep wandering in the change?"
The Tone: Affectionate. Longing. He is genuinely happy to see her, but sad that she is still "out in the cold," hurting herself with empathy when she could be safe and numb with them. He smiles, a secret shared between siblings. "We miss you," his eyes say.
The Exchange with Orion (The Contract)
Varon shifts his attention to Orion, switching seamlessly to flawless Tamrielic. He produces a small, nondescript potion bottle wrapped in a scrap of parchment and holds it out.
The Delivery: He presents the item not as a gift, but as a professional obligation. He explains that the Black Sacrament has been heard in Kynesgrove and that the Listener has designated Orion as the instrument, given his proximity.
The Target Profile: He identifies Hroki, the gate guard who let them into the camp. He explains the nature of the client: a grieving mother in Kynesgrove. He outlines the tragedyΓÇöHroki seduced the woman's son, convinced him to join the Stormcloaks for glory, and the boy died in his first skirmish. The mother does not want justice; she wants revenge for the theft of her son's life.
The Methodology: Varon offers no specific plan, but he highlights the tactical environment. He points out that Hroki is currently assigned to rear guard dutyΓÇösafe and boring. He suggests that "accidents" happen frequently during sieges, especially when soldiers are eager to prove themselves on the front lines.
OrionΓÇÖs Tactical Options (Observations)
Orion is left holding the contract, observing the target (Hroki) in the distance. He analyzes the possibilities available in this specific environment.
The Vanguard Strategy: He considers using his status as a "Hero of Kynesgrove" to influence Galmar or Hroki herself. If he can convince her that she is needed at the frontΓÇöappealing to her vanity or desire for gloryΓÇöshe would be moved into the kill zone of the siege mages, ensuring a death that looks like a casualty of war.
The Poison Strategy: He looks at the potion Varon handed him. He assesses the food and drink Hroki keeps at her post. He calculates the risk of slipping the toxin into her waterskin while the camp is distracted by the coming assault.
The Direct Approach: He evaluates the chaos of the upcoming breach. He considers shadowing her during the fighting, waiting for the confusion of melee to deliver a precise strike amidst the enemy fire, masking the assassination as a lucky shot by a Draugr.

3. The Blessed Carrier (Alfonso)
The Scene: The Triage Tent
Alfonso enters the medical tent, ostensibly to help or scout for supplies. The air inside is hot and fetid, heavy with the copper tang of blood and the sweet, cloying scent of gangrene. The Stormcloak healers are overwhelmed, moving between the screaming wounded, leaving the quiet ones to die in the shadows.
Alfonso finds himself drawn to the darkest corner, where the "hopeless" cases are laid on straw pallets. One soldier, a young Nord whose leg is black with infection, watches Alfonso approach. His eyes are yellowed with jaundice, but they are terrifyingly lucid.
The Recognition
As Alfonso passes, the soldierΓÇÖs hand shoots out, gripping the elfΓÇÖs wrist with feverish strength. He pulls Alfonso down close. He doesn't look at AlfonsoΓÇÖs face; he looks at the air around him, sniffing.
The Whisper: "I smell it," the soldier wheezes, a wet, rattling sound. "The Green DragonΓÇÖs breath. You carry the Order within you, don't you? You are a walking vessel."
The Request (The Taskmaster's Due)
The soldier isn't asking for a cure. He is asking for a promotion. He reveals he is a secret initiate of Peryite, the Taskmaster, who infected himself to bring the blessing to the camp, but his body is failing too fast to spread it effectively.
The Plea: "Don't let this vessel go to waste. The healers... they will burn my body when I die. Such a waste of good potential." He exposes his neck, pulsing with fever. "Breath on me. Accelerate it. Make me a carrier for the afterlife. Turn me into one of His walkers (a Ghoul). Let me serve the Taskmaster even in death."
The Transaction
Alfonso has the choice to use his Patient Zero ability (narratively) to inject his essence into the dying man, ensuring that when he dies in the next hour, he will rise not as a corpse, but as a contagious servant of Peryite.
The Reward: If Alfonso agrees to perform this dark rite, the soldier sighs in ecstasy. He pulls Alfonso closer to whisper a secret.
"In Windhelm. The Gray Quarter. Beneath the stairs of the New Gnisis Cornerclub. There is a door marked with the Dragon's visage. Knock three times and say: 'The lung breathes deep.' The brothers there... they will open the stores for a true servant of the Prince of Pestilence."
The Resolution: The soldier releases his grip, closing his eyes with a smile, waiting for the transformation to take hold. Alfonso leaves him thereΓÇöa time bomb of disease waiting to go off in the heart of the Stormcloak camp, or a resource saved for later.

.
4. The Legend of the Mountain-Breaker (Kyboh)
The Scene: The Training Pit
Kyboh moves toward the sound of steel on steel. Near the siege wall, the Stormcloaks have dug out a sparring pit. It is a ring of packed snow and mud where soldiers work out their frustration. A circle of recruits is cheering as two veterans batter each other with wooden practice swords.
As Kyboh approaches, the sparring stops. The silence spreads outward from the ring. It isn't hostile; it is awestruck.
The Recognition
A young recruit whispers, loud enough to be heard: "That's him. The Cat. I heard he hit a draugr so hard the shockwave cracked the entire barrow."
Another nods, eyes wide. "My cousin lives in Falkreath. Said he punched a vampire back to life."
The Challenge
A massive Nord warrior, stripped to the waist despite the cold, steps out of the ring. He is covered in scars and muscleΓÇöthe camp champion. He doesn't draw a weapon. He holds up a heavy, iron-rimmed training shield, bent and battered from weeks of abuse.
"They say you don't need steel," the champion grunts "They say your hands are hammers. Show us. Show us how you broke a dragon."
He braces the shield, planting his feet in the mud. The crowd closes in, eager for a show. "Hit it! Break it! Show us the Mountain-Breaker!"
The Dilemma
Kyboh looks down at his hands. Under the fused, grey ceramic of the cursed gloves, his bones still ache from the overload. He knows the truth: the "Titan" magic is gone. The gloves are dead weight. If he strikes that iron shield with full force, the recoil will be agonizing. He risks not only injury but humiliationΓÇöif the shield doesn't break, the legend breaks with it.
The Options:
Option A: The Brute Force Gamble (Might Check)
The Action: Accept the pain. Strike the shield with everything he has left in his natural muscles (Might 18), ignoring the agony of the fused gloves reverberating against his shattered bones.
The Risk: If he fails, he just hurts his hand and looks weak. If he succeeds, he maintains the legend but takes 1d20 irreducible damage from the shock to his cursed hands.


Option B: The Master's Lesson (Technique/Agility)
The Action: Don't hit the shield. Hit the man. Use a trip, a redirection, or a pressure point.
The Narrative: "Power is useless if you can't land it."
The Outcome: He drops the champion without striking the iron, preserving his hands and teaching the soldiers that he is a master of martial arts, not just a brute. It changes the legend from "Monster" to "Master."


Option C: The Refusal (Intimidation)
The Action: Stare them down.
The Narrative: "I only break things that are trying to kill me. Do you want to be on that list?"
The Outcome: The crowd backs off, terrified. He keeps his secret, but the soldiers now fear him rather than admire him.


The Result
Depending on his choice, the soldiers react.
If he impresses them: The champion nods, rubbing his arm (or picking himself up). "Iron fists. Good to have you on our side, Cat." The morale of the camp visibly lifts.
If he fails/refuses: The crowd disperses, muttering. The legend loses its shine, and Kyboh feels the weight of the gloves heavier than ever.

Adventure A: Race for the Crown
Section 1: The Siege Lines
Beat 2: The Command Post (The Reunion & The Tactical Deadlock)
The Approach
You leave the relative safety of the rear guard. As you move deeper into the valley, the world narrows. The canyon walls rise high and jagged on either side, trapping the sound of war. The rhythmic thud-hiss of fireballs hitting wet stone becomes a constant percussion.
The snow here is no longer white; it is a slurry of black mud and red slush. Runners sprint past you with bundles of arrows, heads low, eyes wide with the adrenaline of survival. Ahead, a massive stone slabΓÇöpart of the ruin's outer wall that collapsed centuries agoΓÇöserves as the only shield against the death raining from above.
The Bear in the Trap
You round the slab and find the heart of the siege. Galmar Stone-Fist stands amidst a circle of exhausted officers. He is a giant of a man, his bear-pelt armor making him look like a beast standing on two legs. He is not sitting; he is pacing the mud, furious.
A green bolt of magic shrieks over the barricade, exploding against the cliff face ten feet away. Rock shards rain down on the command post. Galmar doesn't even blink. He brushes dust from his shoulder and turns, his hand dropping to the warhammer at his hip.
The Recognition
Galmar Stone-Fist freezes as he locks eyes with Davinia. The fury of the command post vanishes for a heartbeat.
"Davinia?"
He steps over the crate, ignoring the cover, exposing himself to the line of fire to pull her into a crushing, armored hug. It smells of wet fur, iron, and pipe tobaccoΓÇöa scent from her childhood.
"I heard you were in the province, but I thought you'd be sitting in some Solitude counting-house."
He pulls back, holding her by the shoulders. "You look like him. But you've got your mother's fire in your eyes. Does your father know youΓÇÖre out here in the mud with True Nords? Or did you come to save your 'Uncle Galmar' from a cold grave?"
(Allow Davinia to respond. This is her moment to define her relationship with him in front of the party. Is she warm? Professional? Distant?)
The Assessment (Assets on the Board)
An explosion of green flame hits the rock above the trench, showering everyone in dust. GalmarΓÇÖs demeanor shifts instantlyΓÇöthe "Uncle" is gone, and the "General" is back. He turns to scan the rest of the party, looking at them through the lens of a man who needs to win a siege.
To Saijah: He eyes the bow and the Wood ElfΓÇÖs poise. "Bosmer. I assume you can put an arrow in a target before it hears the string? I have two squads of scouts up that ridge who haven't sent a single signal since they crested the rise."
To Kyboh: He looks at the KhajiitΓÇÖs powerful frame and the simple grey wraps on his hands. "A brawler. You look like you can hold a line if the dead get past our shields. I need someone who doesn't panic when the space gets tight."
To Alfonso & Orion: He sniffs the air, catching the faint metallic scent of blood and the static of magic. "A mage and a blade-singer. Specialists. I don't care what your methods are, as long as you're aiming at the ones in the masks."
To Danica: He sees the robes of Kynareth. "A priestess. My medical tent is overflowing, girl. If you have the goddess's favor, weΓÇÖre going to need it."
To Ylva: He gives a gruff nod. "Cleaver. Glad to see you're still breathing."
He looks back to Davinia. "You've brought a rough-looking company, Davinia. But if you vouch for them, I'll use them."

The Strategic Situation (The Deadlock)
Galmar slams his fist onto the charcoal map sketched on a crate.
"We are bleeding for every inch. Look." He points to the massive iron doors at the top of the main causeway.
"That door is the only way in. But the Mages hold the High Balcony directly above it. Artillery. Battlemages. Every time I mass a line to charge the stairs, they drop a wall of fire. I've lost thirty men just trying to reach the first step. It's a kill box."
He gestures angrily at the jagged cliffs flanking the temple entrance on the map.
"And don't bother suggesting the ridges. I already tried to be clever. I sent two squads of my best climbers up the west cliff to flank them. They vanished. No bodies, just... gone. The cliffs are a death trap. The only way is through the fire."
The Objective
Galmar looks at Davinia, his expression grim and exhausted.
"I can keep their attention on the stairs. I'll act as the Anvil. I can feed them targets in the trenches to keep their eyes down. But I cannot breach that door while that artillery is active. If you and your... specialists... can do anything to stop that fire, do it. Otherwise, get clear. I'm ordering the next charge in five minutes."




Adventure A: Race for the Crown
Section 1: The Siege Lines
Beat 3: The Flank (The Hidden Path)
[ENCOUNTER START]
Location: The Goat Path. A secret, treacherous trail winding up the far left cliff face, completely hidden from the main temple entrance.
Terrain:
The Path: 10 feet wide (2 squares). Slick ice.
The Hazard: To the left is the sheer mountain wall. To the right is a 120-foot sheer drop.
Visibility: The path curves around a blind corner ahead.
The Setup:
The party creeps up the path. They round a blind corner and hit the blockade Ulag left for flankers. 
The Wall: 2x Frost Atronachs block the path completely. They are static, waiting.
The Meat: 6x Reanimated Stormcloaks (the missing scouts) stand loosely around them.
The Tether: A green magical line pulses from the zombies, trailing further up the path around the next bend. The Mages are not here; they are at the end of the road, and their magic is sustaining this blockade remotely.
Read Aloud:
"You round the blind corner, the wind howling in your ears. The path ahead is blocked. Two massive Frost Atronachs stand like jagged icebergs, filling the narrow trail. At their feet are the missing scoutsΓÇödead, but standing.
A pulsing green tether connects the corpses to something further up the trail, around the next bend. The mages are up there, unseen, sustaining this trap. The Atronachs turn to face you. They donΓÇÖt have weapons. They just have massive, flat icy palms, ready to push."

The Mechanics: King of the Hill
The Threat:
Infinite Zombies: The zombies regenerate to 10 HP at the start of every round. The source of the necromancy is out of line-of-sight. They cannot be permanently killed here.
Avalanche Shove: The Frost Atronachs do not attack to deal damage. They use their action to Shove.
Mechanic: On a hit, they force a Might Contest. If the Atronach wins, the target is pushed 10 feet.
The Drop: Being pushed off the right side results in a 120-foot fall. Instant death or removal from the battle.


